ğŸ§ª Methods Used
ğŸ“ˆ Centrality Measures
Measure	Description
Degree	Number of direct connections
Betweenness	Frequency of a node lying on shortest paths between others
Closeness	Inverse of average distance to all other nodes
Eigenvector	Influence based on neighbors' importance
PageRank	Google's algorithm ranking nodes by link importance
ğŸ§© Community Detection Algorithms
Algorithm	Type	Description
Louvain	Modularity-based	Optimizes community structure by maximizing modularity
Label Propagation	Diffusion-based	Nodes adopt the majority label of their neighbors
Girvan-Newman	Divisive	Removes edges with high betweenness to split communities
ğŸ“¸ Visualizations
Example: Top 20 Nodes by Degree Centrality

https://images/degree_centrality.png
Example: Community Detection with Louvain

https://images/louvain_communities.png

    All visualizations are saved in the /images folder.

ğŸ“Œ Results & Observations

    The top 10 most central nodes are consistently identified across multiple centrality measures.

    Louvain produces well-balanced communities and runs efficiently on large graphs.

    Label Propagation is extremely fast but less stable across runs.

    Girvan-Newman provides a hierarchical view but is computationally expensive.

    Nodes with high betweenness centrality often act as bridges between communities.

ğŸ§  Conclusion

This project demonstrates how graph mining techniques can reveal hidden structures in social networks. By combining centrality analysis with community detection, we gain insights into:

    Who the key players are

    How communities are organized

    Which algorithms are best suited for different types of network analysis

ğŸ“š References

    Stanford SNAP: Facebook Dataset

    NetworkX Documentation: https://networkx.org/

    Louvain Method: Blondel et al. (2008)

    Girvan-Newman Algorithm: Girvan & Newman (2002)

